{
  "doc_id": "18669",
  "text": "CHI3L1, a gene encoding YKL-40, a marker of the glioblastoma mesenchymal subtype, is overexpressed in glioblastoma cancer stem cells [CITATION_1] . Inactivation induces a loss of aggressiveness and leads to modification of neurotrophin receptor expression [CITATION_2] . CHI3L1 is more highly expressed in glioblastoma than in normal brain [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Previously, we observed in glioblastoma cell lines that CHI3L1 might be a cancer stem cell biomarker in glioma, based on glycosylation-related gene expression analysis, and may be a potential biomarker of aggressiveness [CITATION_5] . Thus, the present study confirmed that CHI3L1 expression significantly differed between grade II and III glioblastoma and that changes in CHI3L1 expression level were associated with glioma prognosis, as reported by Steponaitis et al. [CITATION_6] . A recent meta-analysis of 1241 glioblastoma patients confirmed our results by showing that high CHI3L1 expression was associated with poor prognosis (HR = 1.46; 95% CI, 1.33-1.61; p < 0.001) [CITATION_7] .",
